a(S'The first practical ICs were invented by Jack Kilby at Texas Instruments and Robert Noyce at Fairchild Semiconductor.[49] Kilby recorded his initial ideas concerning the integrated circuit in July 1958, successfully demonstrating the first working integrated example on 12 September 1958.[50] In his patent application of 6 February 1959, Kilby described his new device as "a body of semiconductor material ... wherein all the components of the electronic circuit are completely integrated".[51][52] Noyce also came up with his own idea of an integrated circuit half a year later than Kilby.[53] His chip solved many practical problems that Kilby\'s had not. Produced at Fairchild Semiconductor, it was made of silicon, whereas Kilby\'s chip was made of germanium.'
