a(S'Linear programming'
p4130
g2082
tp4131
a(S'When searching for optimal solutions to a linear function bound to linear equality and inequality constraints, the constraints of the problem can be used directly in '
p4132
g2082
tp4133
a(S'producing the optimal solutions. There are algorithms that can solve any problem in this category, such as the popular simplex algorithm.[57] Problems that can be solved '
p4134
g2082
tp4135
a(S'with linear programming include the maximum flow problem for directed graphs. If a problem additionally requires that one or more of the unknowns must be an integer '
p4136
g2082
tp4137
a(S'then it is classified in integer programming. A linear programming algorithm can solve such a problem if it can be proved that all restrictions for integer values are '
p4138
g2082
tp4139
a(S'superficial, i.e., the solutions satisfy these restrictions anyway. In the general case, a specialized algorithm or an algorithm that finds approximate solutions is used, '
p4140
g2082
tp4141
a(S'depending on the difficulty of the problem.'
p4142
g2082
tp4143
a(S'Dynamic programming'
p4144
g2082
tp4145
a(S'When a problem shows optimal substructures , meaning the optimal solution to a problem can be constructed from optimal solutions to subproblems , and overlapping'
p4146
g2082
tp4147
a(S'subproblems, meaning the same subproblems are used to solve many different problem instances, a quicker approach called dynamic programming avoids recomputing '
p4148
g2082
tp4149
a(S'solutions that have already been computed. For example, Floyd,Warshall algorithm, the shortest path to a goal from a vertex in a weighted graph can be found by using '
p4150
g2082
tp4151
a(S'the shortest path to the goal from all adjacent vertices. Dynamic programming and memoization go together. The main difference between dynamic programming and '
p4152
g2082
tp4153
a(S'divide and conquer is that subproblems are more or less independent in divide and conquer, whereas subproblems overlap in dynamic programming. The difference '
p4154
g2082
tp4155
a(S'between dynamic programming and straightforward recursion is in caching or memoization of recursive calls. When subproblems are independent and there is no '
p4156
g2082
tp4157
a(S'repetition, memoization does not help; hence dynamic programming is not a solution for all complex problems. By using memoization or maintaining a table of '
p4158
g2082
tp4159
a(S'subproblems already solved, dynamic programming reduces the exponential nature of many problems to polynomial complexity.'
p4160
g2082
tp4161
a(S'The greedy method'
p4162
g2082
tp4163
a(S'A greedy algorithm is similar to a dynamic programming algorithm in that it works by examining substructures, in this case not of the problem but of a given solution. Such '
p4164
